Main task is to build a Machine Learning system that predicts whether an employee is likely to leave the company
based on factors like job satisfaction, salary, work-life balance, years at the company, and performance ratings.

This analysis examined employee data to understand why employees leave the organization and to identify groups that
may be at a higher risk of resigning. Overall, 16.12% of employees left the company, meaning approximately 1 in 
every 6 employees resigned.

The analysis found that employees in the Sales department experienced the highest turnover, with 20.63% leaving the
organization. Among job roles, Sales Representatives had the highest exit rate at 39.76%, indicating that this group
may require additional support and retention efforts.

Work-life balance also showed a clear relationship with employee turnover. Employees who reported the lowest work-life
balance rating had an attrition rate of 31.25%, more than double that of employees with better work-life balance ratings.
Additionally, employees were most likely to leave during their first one to two years with the company, suggesting that
the early stages of employment are the most critical for retention.

Several predictive approaches were evaluated to identify employees who may be at risk of leaving. The logistic regression model 
performed well in identifying potential attrition cases, providing HR with a practical tool to proactively identify 
high-risk employees and intervene before they resign.

